      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 88:8, 18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But as intimate acquaintances, especially in a primitive and comparatively unwelded state of society, are generally found within the circle of kinsfolk, the word may be used, and is here used, in reference to a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "kinsman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Vulgate translates it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "consanguineus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The translation is interpretatively correct; but the original term is less definite, and hence, in virtue of the ambiguity, there is not absolute redundancy in the appended clause, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of the family",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "elan of Elimelech",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This friend of Naomi on her husband s side is said, in King James's version, to be ",
        "children": []
      },
